metadata.name: Suspension #57
metadata.description:
Suspension uses simple objects to create structures suspended in space, held together by relation and composition.

The unique composition algorithm is random enough to produce infinite variations, but ordered enough to produce engaging artworks that are instantly recognizable.

Suspension uses negative space, additive coloring, and a unique rendering technique to create a very distinct style. 

It has many hand tuned palettes, with rare palettes that produce incisive variations.

Suspension is responsive and will render fast at any resolution. It looks great on wide screens of 2K, 4K or larger.

To accommodate the variation in displays, you can use the up/down arrow keys to adjust the brightness. 'r' resets to the default values.

's' will save an image in the exact size of the window, so you can create images in any resolution.

metadata.name: GOLENS #162
metadata.description:
"- May every star in the sky become a life?"
"- Yes, and I'll call them golens!

Have you ever noticed how morbid it is? People make wishes to shooting stars. Do they not understand? What can a star, desperate, in the midst of a suicidal fall, give you? She just wants to die at ocean.

Tonight the stars will not fall, they will rise, and they'll be watching our end, we'll die in the ocean.


GOLENS are generative created.
- 15 Body Parts ( not on traits )
- 6 Hierarchy Grades.
- 9 Sky.
- 4 Weathers.
- 9 Powers.


by Gen Doodler | twitter.com/GenDoodler

metadata.name: Sprocket Factory #493
metadata.description:
Just an ordinary scene from a typical day, working as a Sprocket Factory engineer. Inspiration for this work is drawn from the composable nature of blockchain smart contracts and the flow of value between networks of autonomous machines and free-willed individuals.

"A Doodle, Ringer, and Fidenza walk into a Space Bar..."

- Live renderer best viewed in Chrome.
- Press "P" to export an PNG raster image (10k resolution.)
- Press "S" to export an SVG vector.

metadata.name: Pixel Tunnel II #18
metadata.description:
This is based on a technique I've used to create textured abstract art by starting with a base design and applying millions of small mutations. Each design has a minimum of 1,500,000 mutations.

This design is built in 2 phases.
Phase 1: Aggressive twisted pixel tunnels create a tangled root system.
Phase 2: Less aggressive straight lines break up the sharp root systems and make the colors blend together.

- Higher themes are more rare (50 max)
- Higher patterns are more rare (15 max)

metadata.name: Kinetics #280
metadata.description:
CONTROLS
 * Pause a Kinetic by clicking on the canvas.
 * Increase and decrease the p5js framerate by tapping the left and right arrows.
 * Pause the top layer by tapping down arrow.
 * Save a frame by tapping S.
 * Press H for High Quality, M for Default, L for Low Quality. Note, this effects performance.
 * Reset the Kinetic by by tapping backspace.

Kinetics is a neo-constructivist generative art project built using p5js. Each Kinetic delicately moves from it's origin, giving the appearance of infinite space and possibility. The viewer witnesses the construction of the Kinetic floating inside of the negative. Shapes and lines move around the Kinetic in a dazzling display of contrasting color.

The texture developed for Kinetics, deemed The Creation of the Universe (See top right) is at its core a color gradient of 3 different colors. Each piece construct's itself, drawing lines on top of lines to create a unique self contained assembly of materials as opposed to a realistic abstraction. The Creation of the Universe repeats itself in each piece, just as cells do in an organic structure. From here is where it initially got it's name.

Inspired heavily by the works of Rodchenko and Tatlin, each Kinetic appears to slot together like a puzzle. Each piece has multiple hard edge planes clashing aggressively with each other giving the sense that there is more than just a flat canvas. A quasi realism is created through our desire to build instead of simply paint.

"Long Live Generative Art"

- Mitchell

metadata.name: pang #132
metadata.description:
Within each of us resides an evolutionary history of primal emotions, yet we often spend our lives dulling and controlling these instincts rather than reveling in them. Art is one of the ways we best express those instincts and intuitions – accessing and visualizing their visceral qualities, and releasing our deepest emotions in a way we can share.

pang reflects emotions that take control of our impulses – anguish, euphoria, obsession. By using crayon-like marks, the artworks convey the catharsis felt while drawing with a childlike abandon. To capture what gives such marks true feeling, the works deliberate the intrinsic movements, pressures, and angles shaped by hands in various moods. These qualities and their frenetic meanderings represent the infinite possibilities of where the crayon could go next – if only we could free ourselves from the layers of control we've built.

The contradictions we struggle with are reflected throughout the works:  in the long, methodical, and mathematical path to creation that yields work that looks fast, free and unrehearsed;  through the randomly-informed computer generation of art that feels human;  and by the depiction of long-standing traditional techniques to help display the conceptual range of a young, innovative art movement still establishing its pivotal place in the canon of art. These tensions parallel the work's underlying concept, accentuating the suspicion that a learned fear of emotional expression might just be the source of our own pang. 

Created in p5.js, pang is inspired by the emotional works and processes of later abstract expressionists such as Cy Twombly and Joan Mitchell – as well as contemporary artists like José Parla.

Functionality: 
Press ‘p’ to save as a png. 
Press ‘b’ to render with (or without) a transparent background.
Press 0-9 to render at varying degrees of quality.  0 (lowest quality) to 9 (highest quality, 15000 pixels lengthwise).
Press ⬆️ (arrow up) to incrementally increase pixel density.
Press ⬇️ (arrow down) to incrementally decrease pixel density.

__________
TENDER x abstractment
April 2022
